B.KU=new A.co("three_minute_breathing","Three Minute Breathing","A foundational breathing practice using 4-7-8 technique: inhale for 4 seconds, hold for 7, exhale for 8. This pattern activates the parasympathetic nervous system for natural relaxation and stress relief.","breathing_practices","assets/sounds/meditation/guided/breathing_practices/Three Minute Breathing.mp3",215,"Peter Morgan",B.Pz,"This guided practice introduces the scientifically-backed 4-7-8 breathing technique developed by Dr. Andrew Weil. The extended exhale phase naturally triggers your body's relaxation response, making it ideal for reducing anxiety and promoting calm.","You'll be guided through rhythmic breathing cycles that may initially feel challenging but become more natural with practice. Many people notice immediate calming effects, with some experiencing slight dizziness (normal) as your body adjusts to increased oxygen.",B.Nz,null,null)
B.PW=s(["beginner","breath","mindfulness","box-breathing","focus"],t.s)
B.Wo=new A.p9("Breath of life: the respiratory vagal stimulation model","https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6189422/","Gerritsen, R.J. & Band, G.P.","Research on how rhythmic breathing patterns enhance focus and decision-making")
B.Q2=s([B.Wo],t.A5)
B.Ln=new A.co("five_minute_breathing_ucla","Five Minute Breathing","Box breathing practice (4-4-4-4 pattern) used by Navy SEALs and meditation practitioners. Equal intervals of inhale, hold, exhale, hold create rhythmic neural entrainment for enhanced focus and reduced stress.","breathing_practices","assets/sounds/meditation/guided/breathing_practices/Five Minute Breathing.mp3",331,"UCLA MARC",B.PW,"Box breathing, also known as tactical breathing, is extensively used by military units and first responders for stress management. This practice creates balanced autonomic nervous system activation, improving both focus and calm.","The equal timing may feel mechanical at first, but creates a meditative rhythm. You'll likely notice improved focus and a sense of balanced alertness without anxiety.",B.Q2,null,null)
B.P6=s(["breath","awareness","intermediate","sleep-prep","relaxation"],t.s)
B.Wl=new A.p9("Self-regulation of breathing as primary treatment for anxiety","https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10484-015-9279-8","Jerath, R., et al.","Clinical research on exhale-focused breathing for sleep and anxiety relief")
B.QI=s([B.Wl],t.A5)
B.Ld=new A.co("six_minute_breath_awareness","Six Minute Breath Awareness","Sleep-inducing breathing with 4:6 ratio (4 seconds inhale, 6 seconds exhale). The extended exhale activates the vagus nerve and parasympathetic nervous system for natural sleep preparation.","breathing_practices","assets/sounds/meditation/guided/breathing_practices/Six Minute Breath Awareness.mp3",392,"Melbourne Mindfulness Centre",B.P6,"This practice uses the optimal 4:6 breathing ratio for sleep induction. Research shows that longer exhales than inhales consistently activate the body's natural sleep mechanisms without the stress of extreme breath holds.","You'll feel progressively more relaxed as the extended exhales signal your nervous system to prepare for rest. This is excellent preparation for sleep or deep relaxation.",B.QI,null,null)
B.Q4=s(["intermediate","breath","extended","anxiety-relief","physiological-sigh"],t.s)
B.Wm=new A.p9("Brief structured respiration practices enhance mood","https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9860365/","Balban, M.Y., et al.","Stanford research showing physiological sighs as most effective for anxiety reduction")
B.OI=s([B.Wm],t.A5)
B.KX=new A.co("ten_minute_breathing","Ten Minute Breathing","Physiological sigh breathing (4:8 ratio) based on Stanford neuroscience research. This 2:1 exhale-to-inhale ratio maximally activates the parasympathetic nervous system for rapid anxiety reduction.","breathing_practices","assets/sounds/meditation/guided/breathing_practices/Ten Minute Breathing.mp3",596,"Peter Morgan",B.Q4,"Based on Dr. Andrew Huberman's Stanford research on physiological sighs, this pattern provides the most effective breathing technique for rapid anxiety reduction. The 2:1 exhale ratio eliminates breath holds that can increase stress in beginners.","You may notice almost immediate anxiety relief as this pattern directly targets your nervous system's stress response. The longer exhales help discharge tension and promote calm.",B.OI,null,null)
